to a primordial calling out to respond to this beauty. We are, the author suggests, at the very core of our being, summoned to what she terms world spectatorship. Drawing on Heidegger’s phenomenological elaboration of care as the being distinctive of human being and the primarily Lacanian conceptualization of the language of desire specific to each human subject, this metapsychology of love attempts to integrate issues in the fields of psychoanalysis, philosophy, visual culture, art history, and literary and film studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361863340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503618633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503618633/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles